comment:
i do hope that mamdani wins. however, i am not one who buys into any socialist fantasy. i have yet to see a socialist of any kind who can lay a rightful claim to being a true radical (which i am). those who claim to represent 'working people' should acknowledge a few basic facts about work, workers, etc. i do not claim to know all the relevant facts; but i propose a few here: 1) all human beings are heterotroph beings, meaning that they cannot possibly produce the life energies that they need ---they feed on other living beings for their survival; 2) the most glorious economic activity on this planet that living beings are responsible for (with this qualification, i temporarily look away from our greatest benefactor: the sun) is photosynthesis; 3) unlike prime pollinators such as honey bees, other insects, birds, etc., human beings are animals that cannot take much credit for photosynthesis; 4) consequently, human beings should admit that all the work that they do on this planet pales miserably in comparison to the work of those species that are responsible for the current level of photosynthesis; 5) at present, much of human work ends up depleting scarce resources, and thus condemning future generations to worse poverty; 6) human beings have long been responsible for the extinction of other species. even before the advent of agriculture, our distant ancestors killed off megafauna; 7) since the widespread adoption of agriculture, human harmfulness to biodiversity increased exponentially; 8) with the so-called industrial revolution, large segments of human beings (certainly not everybody) increased their contribution to environmental destruction, pollution, and the depletion of scarce resources.
socialists of various kinds all failed to provide, or even envisage, a viable path to try to undo the cumulative harm that our species has been causing on this planet. socialists do not propose any long-term plan for rendering agriculture unnecessary, even centuries into the future. they do not even propose ways of significantly cutting down industrial output (and pollution). instead, they pat themselves on the back for being 'radical' enough to advocate for a more equitable re-distribution of the 'loot' that human beings accumulate through their work that keeps hurting other species, and even causing the extinction of some species. some of them go beyond patting themselves on the back, and drooling all over themselves. they also imagine that they are the 'kelvin zero' of radicalism; that is, you cannot possibly be more radical than them. if you claim to be be more radical than them, some of them will consider locking you up in a lunatic asylum (if they do not execute you as a traitor).
most socialists turn a blind eye to the many forms of intergenerational harm (i.e. the ways in which a generation can lay waste to and/or diminish scarce resources that could have been left aside for future generations). to them, the 'alpha' and the 'omega' of economic harm is the 'exploitation' of the workers by those who own the means of production. they certainly refuse to recognize the glaringly obvious fact that all current economic systems on the planet steal from those human beings who do not procreate, and subsidize some of those who procreate. (some procreators are abandoned to their misery, in certain economic systems.)
i wonder if any of what i wrote will make anyone pause to ponder whether free child-care does anything to help ease the destructiveness of our species on this planet.
some of us are painfully aware that each and every political party in this country, including tiny ones, is pronatalistic. some of us do compute that free child-care entails outright theft from nonprocreators (if nonprocreator is not a word that is in your lexicon, that is not my fault), as well as a possible theft from future generations. some of us also understand that rents may come down in a given town/city/megapolis, if the overall human population there steadily decreases. free child-care is not conducive to moving in that direction.
those who have enough sense to recognize the glory of photosynthesis should also recognize that trees are among the most precious workers. a realistic 'workers' paradise' should, therefore, have more trees, fewer people.
(for those who are wondering, i am a 63-year-old man who never fathered a child. i have lived in new york for more than 36 years, spending most of my earnings on rent, knowing full well that my rent kept subsidizing the procreation of my neighbors (who, like me, belong to the most destructive species on this planet). currently, i am broke and homeless. i have never been a socialist of any kind; but i dutifully work with them in various anti-war and 'progressive' movements. i currently 'carry water' for those who campaign for mamdani --but i choose not to censor myself. those who click on my 'pen name', and follow the links can see some of my video recordings and interviews posted on youtube. my radicalism owes nothing to socialists; and i am accustomed to not getting fair treatment by them.)

comment:
just to offer a quick background before my comment ‚Äî i‚Äôm writing this in response to the wave of racist and islamophobic remarks under candidate mamdani‚Äôs latest three-way debate video. 

so many people are warning others about his so-called ‚Äúhidden islamic agenda,‚Äù as if being muslim automatically means america is doomed. 

these kinds of comments only expose how deep the ignorance still runs ‚Äî and how easily people believe what they‚Äôre told without questioning the source.

it‚Äôs honestly ironic. many of these same people claim that ‚Äúthe media always lies‚Äù and ‚Äúeverything is fake news.‚Äù but somehow, when the media spreads fear about islam or muslims, suddenly it‚Äôs no longer fake ‚Äî it‚Äôs absolute truth. that contradiction alone says a lot about the kind of selective thinking and deep-seated bias that facts can rarely fix.

i fully support a society free from alcohol, gambling, prostitution, usury, children born out of wedlock, elderly parents abandoned to die in nursing homes, child predators, and sex trafficking ‚Äî a world where children can safely play in the streets without fear of being kidnapped. 

these are just some of the many moral and ethical improvements islam can bring to our increasingly decaying societies. of course, people are always free to stick with the current status quo if they choose.

but here‚Äôs what most people don‚Äôt realize ‚Äî islam is not new to america. it‚Äôs as old as america itself. more than a hundred years before this country was even founded, 

muslims were already here, leaving behind written records, legacies, and communities of faith. historians estimate that around 40% of enslaved africans brought to the americas were muslim. despite being violently forced to abandon their faith, many still held on quietly ‚Äî some were buried in their traditional islamic garments, with prayer beads in hand, and their bodies turned toward mecca.

among them were remarkable individuals like omar ibn said, who is buried in fayetteville nc, just one hour away from my home in raleigh nc. he was a west african scholar enslaved in north carolina who left behind arabic writings still preserved today.

also, abdul rahman ibrahima sori, a west african prince enslaved in mississippi who eventually regained his freedom and returned to africa.

and then nicholas said, a muslim man who served honorably in the union army during the civil war. their lives are living proof that islam has long been part of the american story ‚Äî not something foreign or imported.

so whether anyone likes it or not, islam is here, and it‚Äôs been here. and it‚Äôs not coming through the exaggerated western image of muslims with swords and violence. it‚Äôs continuing the same way it has since the 1600s ‚Äî through white and black americans who choose islam and leave behind other beliefs. in fact, a significant portion of american muslims today are exactly that‚Äî not arab immigrants, as so many assume.

so prepare yourself for this change, and even if it takes time, take pride in being part of something deeply transformative ‚Äî a continuation of a legacy that began centuries ago on this very soil.

found this excerpt written by mamdani‚Äôs mother, mira nair (famous filmmaker) reflecting on obama‚Äôs presidential win: 
‚Äúobama's very presence on the national stage implied equality. like all of us, he came from nowhere special. this black guy with a single mom grew up in a small two-bedroom apartment in hawaii, and used his smarts and his discipline to harvard and from there to the presidency.¬† he was an embodiment of what america had been promising the rest of us.

there is no reason the house can't be in session still working. the senate is, and they have passed a couple non-budget bills that can't be implemented until the house also passes them and trump signs them. 

johnson is right about one thing: they need the democrats. so why did house republicans pass the cr without talking to democrats while knowing full well that there would not be 60 votes in the senate.

 multiple votes in the senate has been pure theater. republicans are banking on americans to just believe the rhetoric rather than remembering basic civics or government classes. 

it is baloney that democrats voted for the budget bills. it is true republicans left democrats totally out of drafting those bills then, in some cases, johnson needed democratic votes to pass those bills. this time, democrats told johnson and thune they would not vote for anything else they were left out of.

so let's look at what is really happening. what we learned in civics class. maybe johnson skipped civics - or maybe he is just hoping the american people did. 

normally, a bill is drafted by both parties. the republicans have stated publicly they want to do bills completely without democrats. democrats represent half the country, so by leaving democrats out, republicans are leaving out half the citizens. 

once the cr reached the senate and did not pass, normally it would be opened to amendment or a senate version. why wasn't it? 

the answer is simple: the democrats would have the opportunity to offer an amendment that republicans would have to vote on. please note: republicans aren't being allowed to make amendments either. why not? 

even if the senate passes an amended or senate version, it has to pass the house, and mike johnson adjourned the house. 

thune is making much of the pay and partial funding bills democrats won't vote for. that is also theater. in the case of pay, democrats have a bill to pay all military and government workers. thune won't let them bring it to the floor for a vote. why not? 

even if those bills passed the senate, they would have to pass the house, and they can't because mike johnson adjourned the house. 

this was all set up to force the cr for bills that were prepared without democratic input. 

don't forget the big beautiful bill passed using reconciliation, which requires only a simple majority, not 60 votes. johnson was just plain lying about that. 

the shutdown was caused by forcing democrats to vote for a cr where they had no input. it is a clean cr for other bills where democrats had no input. 

thune won't allow amendments - which he should be allowing. why not? because it would force republicans to vote on them, and thune knows darn well that some republicans have seen the same problems the democrats have. 

mike johnson adjourned the house so if the senate amended the house bill or drafted a senate version, it would have nowhere to go. 

republicans in both chambers were already talking about stand-alone bills to reverse some parts of the bbb. both johnson and thune know those amendments might pass, and they won't allow it. 

this is all a pr show. please don't fall for it. congressional procedures allow for a compromise to end the shutdown. republican leadership won't allow it. 

btw - apparently johnson and many other republicans do not know that communism and socialism are a form of economy, not government. i guess they assume most americans don't know that either. 

they also assume that a democratic socialist believes in socialism. not so! democratic socialists believe in capitalism, but they think a government should offer social programs, most of which we already have. public schools, public roads, fire, police, libraries. but also social security, medicare, medicaid, chip, snap, etc. 

i notice johnson didn't mention which social programs mamdani is proposing. 

as for mamdani being anti-semitic and pro-hamas, that is ludicrous, and it has become a dog whistle to rile up maga republicans. mamdani has publicly condemned hamas, but he has spoken against the slaughter of civilians and denial of aid in gaza.that is pro-life, not pro-hamas. 

but then, johnson has said the 7,000,000,000 no kings protesters are all pro-hamas and far-left socialists/communists, too. yep, a full 2% of american men, women, and children are far-left, pro-hamas terrorists.

comment:
the democratic socialist of america strategy involves:
 * running candidates in democratic primaries: this is how zohran mamdani won his assembly seat and how he is running for mayor. they aim to replace more moderate or centrist democrats with candidates who align with dsa's socialist principles.
 * influencing the party platform: by electing more members and building power, they seek to push the democratic party to adopt more progressive and socialist policies (e.g., medicare for all, green new deal, public ownership of certain services).
 * building an independent electoral infrastructure: while they largely run as democrats, some within dsa also discuss the long-term goal of building independent political power, including their own voter lists, fundraising, and candidate schools. this is sometimes referred to as a "dirty break" strategy ‚Äì working within the democratic party for now but with an eye towards potential independence in the future, if it becomes necessary or viable.
 * "co-governance": as mentioned before, they aim to work with elected officials to pass legislation that aligns with their goals, pushing for reforms from within the system.
key difference: they are not advocating for an armed revolution or the dismantling of the democratic electoral system. they are participating in it to transform it from within, or to leverage it to gain power for their agenda.
so, while they absolutely want to see a significant shift in the democratic party's power structure and policy agenda ‚Äì essentially, for the party to become much more aligned with democratic socialist principles ‚Äì calling it an "overthrow" in the revolutionary sense is misleading and inaccurately equates their methods with those of fidel castro. it's a strategic internal struggle and an electoral movement, not a violent revolution.

this is why trump was so popular in 2015 and 2016, because he did exactly that. he had his finger on the pulse of what actually were all the problems, and he didn't have a problem throwing accusations at even his own side on the things they did to contribute, because it was true, and it's been a long bubbling rage building on both the left and the right for a long time....that the establishment on the left and the right is why we are here today. they continued contributing to the problems, making them worse, all while denying they were even real problems. 

this is also why bernie sanders was so popular, and why bannon has respect for him. bannon is a political strategist at heart, and he fully recognizes the value that being able to correctly identify the problems that the american people face has - he just believes that it's the populist right that has the correct remedies to those problems. 

but he fully recognizes that when it comes to connecting with the people, and getting grassroots support, being able to identify what the problem is, is 80% of the battle. and the populist left, even if their solutions are terrible and will make things worse, will be able to win elections if they stick to their populist principles, and don't get co-opted by the establishment. 

and that's where mamdani comes in - he's a populist. young people look at him and see someone who is able to articulate what the problems are very clearly. and while his solutions would only make things worse, that's not something that most people even look to with any depth - just finding someone that is able to speak to what average americans are dealing with today is going to resonate and connect with them like nothing else will. 

and that's why bannon respects people like mamdani - he's effectively capturing the populist left, by seeing the world how it is. his solutions may be terrible, bannon likely disagrees with every single one of his solutions, but bannon respects the game. if mamdani is able to do the leg work to connect with more people in new york and gain their support by speaking truth to their struggles, then he has earned the win. 

doesn't mean bannon thinks it's going to lead to some prosperous new york or other such nonsense, but this is about political strategy. and anyone that sees how the political landscape has changed drastically since 2015, to recognize that it's now about populism rather than establishment politics, bannon will have respect for that.

comment:
i am australian, but i must add another point about why mamdani was so successful in this primary election, which is not getting as much attention in almost all discussions (except on some more independent shows). that is the depth of anger and absolute disgust americans now have toward the democratic party. while these emotions existed long before november, the betrayal didn't boil over until after democrats forced their voters into their newest man-made federal election farce.

also, americans mustn't underestimate bernie's influence in this race. the america that now exists thanks to his work, dedication, and belief (on most occasions alone) has reopened for them over the last decade. since november, bernie has been proven right on everything he has ever said. while democratic leadership (serving and not serving) is completely missing in action and silent, bernie is standing up as an american leader and sole american statesman. 

now, thanks to the hard work, dedication, and belief of mamdani and his campaign, volunteers, and supporters, americans in new york city have been given the opportunity to elect another excellent leader to represent them as mayor. üòä

mamdani has been attacked on foreign policy issues, and bernie has been laying the groundwork for mainstreaming these issues and openly discussing them. on iran, bernie was alone (outside of three house republicans & senator rand paul, who, from memory, only did for $$ reasons) in congress when trump and congress (...every republican and democrat) destroyed the jcpoa/iran nuclear deal in his first term as president. every republican and democrat in congress coming out now to complain about trump's actions against iran all supported and voted to destroy the jcpoa and snap back all the sanctions the jcpoa removed from iran. 

before 2015, criticising israel or even mentioning palestinians was more than just a taboo & career-ending decision. however, bernie was the most potent american to mainstream criticism of israel and for standing up to its violence.

this is an aside, but as an australian, i find another part of the coverage during this race quite amusing (also pathetically terrifying): watching certain politicians, corporate media, and other "special interest groups" in the us try to explain and discuss rank-choice voting/preferential voting and the absolute fear on their faces and in their voices throughout their "discussions." the desperation to now curtail or ban it for "unfairness" and being "undemocratic" is enjoyable and terrifying in equal measure. 

we've had preferential voting in australia for 124 years (nationally).

comment:
in terms of why polling underestimated mamdani's turnout: i think it is because polls rely on people that are regular voters, or at least are in some voter database somewhere, but mamdani galvanized folks that had either never voted before, or were low-propensity voters for the recent past at least. i keep thinking about the south asian indian/pakistani/bengali neighborhoods of jackson heights as a case study. many folks there are likely low-propensity voters, but they, like many others, saw themselves in mamdani and came out to vote, but many of them are likely not well-captured in any polling data due to their voting history.

polls are just a mathematical way to incorporate the assumptions of a pollster. at some level, they assign numeric weights to their assumptions. this became very clear in this race.
